<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a diff viewer?", answer: "A diff viewer is a tool that compares two pieces of text and highlights the differences between them. It shows which lines were added, removed, or remained unchanged. Diff viewers are commonly used in software development to review code changes, but they are useful anytime you need to compare two versions of any text document." },
  { question: "How does the line-by-line comparison work?", answer: "This tool uses the Longest Common Subsequence (LCS) algorithm to find the optimal alignment between the two texts. It identifies the longest sequence of lines that appear in both texts in the same order, then marks any lines not in the LCS as either additions (present only in the second text) or deletions (present only in the first text)." },
  { question: "Can I compare code files with this tool?", answer: "Yes, this diff viewer works with any plain text including source code, configuration files, documentation, and prose. Simply paste the contents of your two files into the left and right text areas and click Compare. The tool preserves whitespace and indentation for accurate code comparison." },
  { question: "What do the colors mean in the diff output?", answer: "Green lines with a plus sign indicate additions, which are lines present only in the second text. Red lines with a minus sign indicate deletions, lines present only in the first text. Lines without highlighting are unchanged and appear in both texts at the same position in the sequence." },
  { question: "Is there a size limit for the text comparison?", answer: "The comparison runs entirely in your browser, so there is no server-side limit. However, very large texts with thousands of lines may take a moment to process because the LCS algorithm requires comparing every line pair. For best performance, keep comparisons under a few thousand lines." }
]) %>

